                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d683">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.9315 Manchuria/231: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-11T20:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 11, 1940—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 11—1:11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>436. Our 435, June 11, 7 p.m.<note n="36" xml:id="d683fn36">Not printed.</note>
                    Soviet-Japanese agreement concerning delimitation of Manchurian-Outer Mongolia
                    border near Nomonhan. A member of the Foreign Office has informed us in addition
                    to confirming the report of the agreement, that it was merely initialed by
                    Molotov and Ambassador Togo at Moscow and must now be referred to the Mongolian
                    and Manchurian Governments for their <pb facs="0654" n="642" xml:id="pg_642"/>
                    approval. He anticipated no difficulty in this respect, however, and added that
                    the Soviet Union has been adamant about the necessity of settling this border
                    issue before proceeding to take up other outstanding problems such as the
                    conclusion of a long term fisheries agreement and Russian interference with
                    Japanese interests in Soviet Sakhalin. The Japanese press although pleased
                    emphasizes that the settlement of the Nomonhan question constitutes only one of
                    the many problems confronting the two countries.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
